HEADWORD: Mess
<hw>Mess</hw> <pr>(m⟦ecr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mass; church
service.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mess</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mess
<hw>Mess</hw> <pr>(m⟦ecr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>mes</ets>, OF. <ets>mets</ets>, LL. <ets>missum</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>mittere</ets> to put, place (<it>e. g.</it>, on the table), L.
<ets>mittere</ets> to send. See <er>Mission</er>, and cf. <er>Mass</er>
religious service.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A quantity of food set on a
table at one time; provision of food for a person or party for one meal;
<as>as, a <ex>mess</ex> of pottage</as>; also, the food given to a beast
at one time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At their savory dinner set⟦br⟧
Of herbs and other country <qex>messes</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A number of persons who eat together, and for whom
food is prepared in common; especially, persons in the military or naval
service who eat at the same table; <as>as, the wardroom
<ex>mess</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A set of four; -- from the old practice of dividing
companies into sets of four at dinner.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The milk given by a cow at one milking.</def>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[Perh. corrupt. fr. OE. <ets>mesh</ets> for
<ets>mash</ets>: cf. <ets>muss</ets>.]</ety> <def>A disagreeable mixture
or confusion of things; hence, a situation resulting from blundering or
from misunderstanding; <as>as, he made a <ex>mess</ex> of it</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mess</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mess
<hw>Mess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Messed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Messing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To take meals with a mess; to
belong to a mess; to eat (with others); <as>as, I <ex>mess</ex> with the
wardroom officers</as>.</def> <rj><au>Marryat.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mess</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mess
<hw>Mess</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To supply with a
mess.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a mess{5} of; to disorder or muddle; to
muss; to jumble; to disturb; to mess up.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was n't right either to be <qex>messing</qex> another man's
sleep.</q> <rj><qau>Scribner's Mag.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Message</ent>⟦br⟧
